    "markdown": "# Matrices - DETAILED NOTES\n\n## Introduction\n\nMatrices are a fundamental concept in mathematics, widely used in various fields such as computer science, engineering, economics, and physics. They provide a concise way to represent complex data and perform operations on it. In this chapter, we will explore the concept of matrices, its components, and its applications.\n\n## What is a Matrix?\n\nA matrix is a rectangular array of numbers, symbols, or expressions arranged in rows and columns. It is denoted by a capital letter, and its elements are represented by the corresponding lowercase letter with a subscript indicating the position of the element.\n\nExample: Let A be a matrix of order 3 x 4.\n\nA = | a11  a12  a13  a14 |\n    | a21  a22  a23  a24 |\n    | a31  a32  a33  a34 |\n\nThe elements of the matrix are a11, a12, a13, a14, a21, a22, a23, a24, a31, a32, a33, and a34.\n\n## Components / Sub-topics\n\n### Definition\n\n- **Order of a Matrix**: The order of a matrix is the number of rows followed by the number of columns. For example, the order of matrix A is 3x4.\n- **Size of a Matrix**: The size of a matrix is the number of elements it contains.\n\n| Type of Matrix | Definition | Characteristics |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Square Matrix | A matrix with the same number of rows and columns | A11 = A22 = ... = A(nn) |\n| Rectangular Matrix | A matrix with a different number of rows and columns | A11 ≠ A22 ≠ ... ≠ A(nn) |\n| Null Matrix | A matrix with all elements equal to zero | A11 = A12 = ... = A(nn) = 0 |\n| Identity Matrix | A square matrix with all elements equal to zero on the main diagonal and all other elements equal to zero | A11 = A22 = ... = A(nn) = 1, Aij = 0 for i ≠ j |\n\n## Operations on Matrices\n\n### Addition of Matrices\n\nTwo matrices A and B can be added only if they have the same order.\n\nA + B = | a11 + b11  a12 + b12  ...  a1n + b1n |\n         | a21 + b21  a22 + b22  ...  a2n + b2n |\n         | ...        ...        ...        ... |\n         | an1 + bn1  an2 + bn2  ...  ann + bnn |\n\n### Scalar Multiplication\n\nA matrix A can be multiplied by a scalar k.\n\nkA = | ka11  ka12  ...  ka1n |\n     | ka21  ka22  ...  ka2n |\n     | ...    ...    ...    ... |\n     | kan1  kan2  ...  kann |\n\n### Multiplication of Matrices\n\nTwo matrices A and B can be multiplied only if the number of columns in A is equal to the number of rows in B.\n\nAB = | a11b11 + a12b21 + ... + a1nbn1  a11b12 + a12b22 + ... + a1nbn2  ...  a11bn1 + a12bn2 + ... + a1nbnm |\n     | a21b11 + a22b21 + ... + a2nbn1  a21b12 + a22b22 + ... + a2nbn2  ...  a21bn1 + a22bn2 + ... + a2nbnm |\n     | ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    ...    .